<P>
<B>by <A href="mailto:methos@gamersx.com">Methos</a></b>
<P>
These seven statistics effect your character in many different ways. From mana, to damage, to the ability to avoid attack, these characteristics are crucial in creating your Everquest persona.  When creating a character, a player will have a certain about of points (depending on race and class) to add to the base statistics. While there are items and spells that enhance these scores, you will be stuck with them the entire game. In other words, choose wisely.

<P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Strength</B></FONT><P><P>

Strength affects a character in two distinct ways. First, it determines your weight capacity, or how much you can carry. This becomes more apparent in the higher levels, when the stronger, and consequently heavier, armor will weigh down those with small strength scores. Many clerics run into this exact problem. Clerics have the ability to wear plate, and many of the good cleric races have low strength.  Secondly, strength determines the physical damage a character dishes out. Higher level characters will notice a bigger change with diversified strength scores than lower level characters. Considering both effects are rarely seen until tons of time is spent on a character, players often find problems with their strength total too late. I suggest investing in some strength for fighter and cleric classes, although all classes benefit from some extra strength.

<P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Stamina</B></FONT><P><P>

Stamina influences both fatigue and hit points. While fatigue doesn't seem worthwhile, nobody has ever complained about having too many hit points. Pumping points into stamina appears beneficial for characters that stand on the front lines absorbing damage. This attribute is perfect for these fighters. Troll Warriors, which regenerate hit points faster, should looking heartily into investing into this category. Overall, stamina should be a secondary concern though.

<P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Agility</B></FONT><P><P>

Armor Class and the ability to evade enemy attacks is derived from Agility. This attribute is important to all classes in Everquest. Agility allows the melee fighters to last longer, and the spell casters to actually survive when a monster goes berserk on them. This attribute also enhances your armor class is altered by equipment, which can really add up with initial armor types. The effect that Agility has on armor class seems to grow smaller as the armor gets more advanced. If you want a character that can make it through the initial levels easier, then agility seems to work best. However, people who invest in other attributes seem to be stronger during the later levels. It's all up to how a person wants to play their character.

<P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Dexterity</B></FONT><P><P>

Dexterity influences a character's chance of hitting their target, which is nearly the opposite of agility. The exact change in ability to hit has not been determined. Most believe this attribute barely, if at all, enhances the percentage at which hits are landed. Dexterity also supposedly alters a Bard's instrument playing ability.  While it doesn't change the overall effectiveness of the songs, dexterity probably influences how often a song is successful. However, a Bard will receive a message if the song worked or not, and will be able to restart the song in one second. Finally, higher dexterity helps to prevent interruptions when casting spells. This is very important to all spell casters, but more so to those that wish to solo. The ability to actually get some spells off in the face of an imposing beast is nothing to be overlooked. Lower level spell casters will rarely successfully cast through an interrupt, so unfortunately you won't know if your dexterity is high enough for your tastes until tons of time is invested into the character. 

<P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Wisdom</B></FONT><P><P>

Wisdom determines the amount of mana for Clerics, Druids, Paladins, Shaman, and the Ranger. Obviously, wisdom should be the primary concern for these classes. Wisdom also helps against mind-altering spells, such as the charm spells.  

<P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Intelligence </B></FONT><P><P>

Intelligence determines mana for wizards, necromancers, magicians, enchanters, and the shadow knight hybrid. Intelligence will also determine a character's rate of skill advance, so other classes may want to invest in this attribute. My Ogre Shaman and High Elf Cleric both progressed in skills at nearly the same rate. If intelligence does influence skill advance, then it only does so at a very high level. Most melee characters that invested more than a few points into intelligence have grown to regret that decision.

<P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Charisma</B></FONT><P><P> 

Charisma directly affects merchant prices. This is very helpful for spell casters who must purchase many spells throughout their journeys. It obviously doesn't help in negotiations with other players, which hurts the major bonus of this attribute. Charisma also helps a character's ability to change faction standings and enhances the charm spell that enchanters are famous for. Pending future updates to Everquest, certain Bard songs may require mana to play. Charisma is the main attribute for Bards, so it's a good guess that the Charisma score will determine the amount of mana. 

<P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Conclusion</B></FONT><P><P>

These attributes shouldn't be taken lightly, but they also shouldn't be stressed over. Characters with so called "bad attributes" will still be playable, especially if you are more into role-playing in comparison to power gaming. Ogres warriors with twice the strength and stamina of a Dark Elf warriors do not hit for twice the damage,  nor do they have twice the hit points. Considering the mysterious reasons that Verant hides the true game statistics, one can only guess at the exact effect the attributes have on a character. 


